title: I'm currently on the tough decision between a Surface Laptop 7 for Business (13.8") and a Thinkpad X
body: I'm currently on the tough decision between a Surface Laptop 7 for Business (13.8") and a Thinkpad X1 Carbon Gen13. Which one would you pick? Battery life, a good display and built quality would be my most important factors. I'm a bit afraid that the Thinkpad has some kind of soft-touch coating that my current Dell XPS 15 9560 has, which deteriorates after some years and leaves a sticky surface ... The full-metal chassis on the SL7 probably will not have this issue? Display-wise, I think both are great. Since I mainly do productive tasks (browsing, coding), I probably don't necessarily need the nice contrast and perfect blacks of the Thinkpad's OLED display?

title: Bridge networks with mesh access points are still the best. Especially if you use a Linux router on
body:
Bridge networks with mesh access points are still the best. Especially if you use a Linux router on which you can install an AdBlocker. This thing is overpriced hardware. We "only" have WiFi 6, but with all access points together we have up to 4x 2.4GHz and 8x 5/6GHz streams. All together (modem, router, switch and 2x access point): approx. 250 bucks. Full WiFi coverage throughout the property, no advertising, no unwanted services and very stable and fast connections between the devices and the Internet. A total of 13 Ethernet ports instead of just 7 xD.

But seeing this unboxing is still a real pleasure.

title: Not a regular viewer here: this was a banger. Well argued and succinct, and good to see a creative w
body: Not a regular viewer here: this was a banger. Well argued and succinct, and good to see a creative with a large platform taking an actual stance on the use of generative AI in games. I'm a member of a handful of creator programs myself, and my concerns about AI generated content have been met with resistance and conflict avoidance. my peers in the field mysteriously piping up to be like "wow, things are getting heated in here" because I brought up criticism of generative AI, as though critique itself was the issue. And maybe it is for those creators and that context, where criticism is not seen as the act of love that it is, and so to negatively speak about things in their mind risks the connections they have to developers. it's an intensely frustrating experience, so to see the stand you've taken and to say that the game is a "moral failure" is such a breath of fresh air. i look forward to future videos, and will probably head back to see your legacy reviews too. thank you for making this video!

title: The greatest thing about a growth mindset is that infinite and exponential growth is literally impos
body:
The greatest thing about a growth mindset is that infinite and exponential growth is literally impossible. Just like how in the square cube law everything twice as big becomes four times heavier, the more work it takes for large companies to grow further. And because the growth is needed everywhere and tied with quarterly profits to please shareholders that means slowing down short term for long term profit is absolutelly not an option, short term growth only. As growth isnt always possible then profit must be made by cutting costs, and amazingly shooting yourself in the foot by contantly firing workers and making the ones staying work even more unreasonable amouts makes growth EVEN HARDER.
To seek constant growth is fated to end by being crushed by your own weight

title: The craziest part of the ChatGPT story smacked me right in the face while watching the stream highli
body:
The craziest part of the ChatGPT story smacked me right in the face while watching the stream highlights:
Where the hell does 50/50's boat at the end come from?

All four of the squad presumably take the same swimming exit in co-op to escape the lab. All four of them presumably swim to the surface in the same spot. But in the end cutscene, only the guys emerge from the water, and then 50/50 shows up with a speedboat, a Marvel quip, and Kagan loaded in the boat.

Where did she get the /boat/ from? She was with the rest of the team. You were at the bottom of the ocean. At what point could she have /ever/ gone off to get a boat, while also hauling knocked out Kagan with her FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE OCEAN?

The ending is so incomprehensible it couldn't have ever been touched by human hands.

title: There are so many things wrong with this game that I couldn't possibly make a comprehensive list, bu
body:
There are so many things wrong with this game that I couldn't possibly make a comprehensive list, but here are some of my favorites:
-The complete disappearance of any the fun action setpieces of previous games.
-Giant Michael Rooker MMO boss fight.
-Multiple antagonists with clearly very intricate visual designs but barely any screentime, lore or characterization because they exist solely to flesh out the Guild faction for Warzone.

-The hallucinated air drops that do real damage to the very real mechs during the TEMU Shadowheart bossfight.
-The Nightmare Vorkuta escape sequence where we redo the Vorkuta escape mission from Black Ops 1 except with Nightmare zombies and ten times less excitement.
-The AI forgetting to write what happens to Dr. Falkner in the script, so they just abruptly cut to the next scene after he tells them about Sanctum and they never show what the gang does with him.

title: This is why I got into the games industry as a concept artist for a small indie studio wanting to ma
body:
This is why I got into the games industry as a concept artist for a small indie studio wanting to make their first game and have completely avoided AAA studios. 

I wanted to work on these large games as a kid, but the industry is not what I thought it was. Obviously not every AAA studio is akin to Activision-Blizzard with its AI practices, but the thought of using AI as an artist feels like the real creativity is simply gone. 

It is very disheartening to see the reality of my childhood dream. BO7 should show everyone the real result of what happens when you want to maximize profits by laying off as many people as possible and have AI do as much work for you as it can. Pathetic.

title: Stating that "some parts" were generated with AI renders a defense argument (even more) difficult. I
body:
Stating that "some parts" were generated with AI renders a defense argument (even more) difficult. If it is not known specifically what is generated with AI, it is anyone's guess what is. Mentioning AI in the Steam page, for a lack of better word, contaminates the entire perception of the game.
Within that line of thought, it is not 0% usage and it is not 100%, but if it is spread across the whole and not concentrated, it will feel like it is entirely AI-generated.
